{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"124fb082-52e3-4bba-91a5-10317fc3d67f","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look in these locations:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** — the OS automatically generates them:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Files are named like `YourApp_YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS_machinename.ips`. Recent crashes may take a few seconds to appear.\n\n2. **Console.app** — open it and check **Crash Reports** in the sidebar for a formatted view.\n\n3. **Core dumps** — disabled by default on macOS. To enable:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   Then reproduce the crash. The core file typically lands in `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n4. **`log show`** — for additional context:\n   ```bash\n   log show --predicate 'process == \"YourApp\"' --last 5m\n   ```\n\nThe `.ips` crash report in `DiagnosticReports` is usually the easiest starting point — it includes the stack trace, exception type, and faulting address without any prior setup.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5bdabd67-2330-424e-9b34-49a06e24969f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":323,"requestId":"2C5D:281CF9:15FE914:18DEF75:69F94C43"},"id":"8ada84d9-093e-47e0-a9bb-467edbe3cf25","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:47:59.022Z","parentId":"b07add8a-5adc-4ebc-95ac-d84102689bd4"}
